{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 India}} in the 1st and 2nd centuries CE was divided into various states, including the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kushan_Empire"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Kushan Empire}} and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satavahana_dynasty"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Satavahana Kingdom}}. At this point in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Buddhism"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Buddhist history}}, the Buddhist community was already divided into various {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schools_of_Buddhism"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Buddhist schools}} and had spread throughout India. \
At this time, there was already a small and nascent Mah\uc0\u257 y\u257 na movement. Mah\u257 y\u257 na ideas were held by a minority of Buddhists in India at the time. As Joseph Walser writes, "Mah\u257 y\u257 na before the fifth century was largely invisible and probably existed only as a minority and largely unrecognized movement within the fold of nik\u257 ya Buddhism."{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagarjuna#cite_note-6"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [6]}} By the second century, early {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahayana_sutras"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Mah\uc0\u257 y\u257 na S\u363 tras}} such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A%E1%B9%A3%E1%B9%ADas%C4%81hasrik%C4%81_Praj%C3%B1%C4%81p%C4%81ramit%C4%81_S%C5%ABtra"}}{\fldrslt 
\f4\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A\uc0\u7779 \u7789 as\u257 hasrik\u257  Praj\'f1\u257 p\u257 ramit\u257 }} were already circulating among certain Mah\uc0\u257 y\u257 na circles\
Some scholars such as Joseph Walser argue that N\uc0\u257 g\u257 rjuna was an advisor to a king of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satavahana_dynasty"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 S\uc0\u257 tav\u257 hana}} dynasty which ruled the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deccan_Plateau"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Deccan Plateau}} in the second century.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagarjuna#cite_note-:1-9"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [9]}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagarjuna#cite_note-:2-10"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [10]}} This is supported by most of the traditional hagiographical sources as well.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagarjuna#cite_note-:3-11"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [11]}} Archaeological evidence at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amaravati_Stupa"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amar\uc0\u257 vat\u299 }} indicates that if this is true, the king may have been {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yajna_Sri_Satakarni"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Yaj\'f1a \uc0\u346 r\u299  \u346 \u257 takar\u7751 i}} (c. second half of the 2nd century). On the basis of this association, N\uc0\u257 g\u257 rjuna is conventionally placed at around 150\'96250 CE.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagarjuna#cite_note-:1-9"}}{\fldrslt 
